ce:section.ce:para:
The effect of some metal ions such as Na+, K+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Zn2+, Cu2+, Hg2+, Fe3+, Cd2+, Ni2+, Sn2+, Pb2+, Cr(VI), Al3+, Ag+ and Au3+ on the fluorescence intensity of GQDs was investigated. As shown in Fig. 3
                        , compared to the other metal ions that have negligible effects on the fluorescence intensity, Au3+ ions could significantly diminish the fluorescence intensity of GQDs. According to the literatures, carbon nanomaterials could serve as the electron donor in the reaction with electron-withdrawing agents. For example, the electron donating ability of carbon dots was confirmed in the photoreduction of noble metal salts into their respective metals (silver, gold, and platinum) [46,47]. Moreover, Shen et al. reported that C-dots show the capability for direct reduction of Ag+ to AgNPs without additional reducing agent or external photoirradiation [48]. According to these results, we suspected that GQDs could serve as the electron donor for the reduction of Au(III) to AuNPs. The appearance and progressive increases of the gold plasmon absorption confirmed the formation of AuNPs (Fig. 4
                        ). Moreover it can be seen from Fig. 3, which Au(III) has more remarkable quenching effect on c-GQDs than on g-GQDs. This may be attributed to the presence of carboxylate group in c-GQDs (see the FTIR spectra in Fig. S2, ESM). These GQDs can bind to Au(III) ions through their carboxylate groups, which may lead to better stabilization of produced AuNPs and more efficient electron and/or energy transfer. There are two possible pathways for quenching of GQDs fluorescence: the fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET) from GQDs to AuNPs, as fluorescence quenchers, and the common electron transfer from GQDs to Au(III). As shown in Fig. S4, the absorption spectrum of produced AuNPs has high overlap with fluorescence spectrum of GQDs, which indicate the possibility of the FRET process.
